7EDE8ED04DB84E72962B7EBD147764EE.description:
Create a timeline depicting how humans have employed engineering and technology to
maximize use of microorganisms, plants, and animals for various purposes. Choose one specific example and construct an argument supporting or opposing the use of engineering or
technology in this instance.

F5836AE53A9C482580EFE4384930DBB9.description:
Construct an explanation for how classification schemes have changed based on new evidence
gained due to advances in biotechnology.

74E42856A21C400D977B4611096D5456.description:
Research the development of the microscope and advances in microscopy technology for the
discovery and ongoing understanding of microorganisms.

CB2CC8F169A742219EA801688CCBFA7E.description: Links Among Engineering, Technology, Science, and Society

7966267F06FE41B0A7FDA0991C824E77.description: Evaluate scientific data collected from multiple sources to trace animal evolution

BB0D919268394A7F9CDBF9934E121F58.description:
Model several reproductive strategies used by example organisms and compare them to explain
how each differentially accomplishes reproductive success. Collect information in support of the
argument that rapidly reproducing species that produce more young are more resilient.

1157330B3A394EBBB077CC46B8FAB762.description:
Gather and analyze data on ectothermic and endothermic organisms and argue the advantages
and disadvantages these organisms possess, considering various environments in which they live
and various strategies for survival.

AF07491652D744FBBBF5442B6EB99030.description:
Create a model demonstrating how the immune system functions in monitoring of and
responding to bacterial and viral infectious diseases.

E25B70A4D22F47F2B72ADE8D570C7510.description:
Obtain and communicate information on how the nervous and endocrine systems in a model
vertebrate organism coordinate body functions such as: growth and development; stimuli
response and information transmission; and, the maintenance of homeostasis.

4E43E486B0F848D2BF216B3DCB702255.description:
Design and carry out an investigation examining how major body systems interact to maintain
homeostasis of nutrient, energy, water, waste, and/or temperature balance.

C22F4167EBE647019F7BBD492420AAA5.description:
Observe examples of organisms from major animal phyla in order to describe the diverse
structures associated with the following functions: gas exchange; energy acquisition; nutrient
processing and distribution; environmental responses; and reproduction.

687F1E902B3145609305535DD310CEE2.description:
Construct an argument for the importance of embryological development in understanding
relatedness (evolutionary relationships). As part of the argument, compare models of
embryological development of protostomes and deuterostomes.

83A7365160FD4A0BBD85E99E665456BB.description:
Create a model to distinguish animal germ layers (endoderm, mesoderm, and ectoderm) and
resulting tissue types. Use the model to make predictions regarding phylogenetic relationships
among groups of organisms with varying body plans.

64F84D9BA8DB46A0AF5470E4CA8A9E75.description:
Investigate the role of different plant types in ecosystem building and maintenance (examples:
soil formation, inhibition of erosion, oxygen production, carbon sequestration, habitats).

C007D7A83F704ED181C5564EC5900656.description:
Create an argument from evidence regarding the importance of plant relationships including
symbiosis and co-evolutionary relationships (examples: mycorrhizae, Rhizobium, pollination,
etc.).

42A5C3822263412F88C6CCB76694D88C.description:
Develop a model explaining plant tropisms at different scales (cell, tissue, organ, system). Use
the model to predict how plants will respond in various environmental conditions.

54495222B7654A2693C0D9B04AA86A91.description: Design and carry out an investigation examining the function of plant hormones.

A95DB86C11A248CE91A50AC1CE4DA177.description:
Use a model angiosperm to differentiate plant organs and the tissues from which they are
made. Use the model to explain how the plant structures: provide support; regulate gas
exchange; obtain and use energy; and, process and distribute nutrients.

F08F79652E1F4B6CB3E956F09ABF3E57.description:
Obtain information and ask questions about the advantages and disadvantages of the basic
plant life cycle (alternation of generations). Compare variations in this life cycle among major
groups of plants.

86D8E1F666914E95AB9E973ACC4087F7.description:
Interpret data supporting current plant classification schemes. Use a dichotomous key to
identify plants based on variations in characteristics.

D4C3B3E6ADBA4722883CFF789CDB0CA0.description:
Analyze evolutionary relationships among algae and major groups of plants. In this analysis,
consider adaptations necessary for survival in terrestrial habitats.

7F0917283BCA414685A5036BD0E6E7CD.description:
Using models, compare how the following processes occur in major groups of fungi: gas
exchange; nutrient distribution; energy acquisition and use; response to internal and external
stimuli; and, reproduction.

E0A4158A64CD484892119276E87D0E19.description:
Evaluate information regarding the diversity of protists. Use this information to analyze
evolutionary relationships among protists, fungi, plants, and animals.

0AA5C4AD7AB14D1CA85FA46B798CB767.description:
Using models, compare how the following processes occur in major groups of protists: gas
exchange; nutrient distribution; energy acquisition and use; response to internal and external
stimuli; and, reproduction.

018948402327416D8807428FE445E1C0.description:
Construct an explanation for the evolution of eukaryotes and multicellularity based on evidence
supporting the theory of endosymbiosis. Consider examples of extant organisms (viruses,
bacteria, and protists) that invade host cells.

FA81B0AA59D5489B8BD2E2F83B3E4450.description:
Using models, compare how the following processes occur in major groups of bacteria: gas
exchange; nutrient distribution; energy acquisition and use; response to internal and external
stimuli; and, reproduction.

29E4309BDFA64F72A2B451F6742845A4.description:
Obtain information and compare features of Bacteria and Archaea. Ask questions about the
evolution of each group.

59E25E051A1848A6BAC93F653253F2FA.description:
Construct an argument from evidence supporting the three domain classification system or
opposing the system with a suggested alternative system.

4CBC76971DC944F18D79074641BFB1D3.description:
Trace changes in classification schemes over time, explaining these changes considering new
findings and new interpretations of existing data.

505508D3932C4723A0C0D731C4245B65.description:
Use molecular data to construct cladograms depicting phylogenetic relationships between major
groups of organisms.

5ED9AE3FE9304FF798E9C5A46BDF1E51.description:
Using information based on the geologic time scale and history of life on Earth, look for patterns
in changes in organisms over time and explain how these patterns support the theory of
evolution.

CC859B768A6F4819A90201C99B2F4C2D.description:
Use models of viruses, prokaryotes, and eukaryotes to ask questions about characteristics of
living things and analyze theories regarding the origin of life on Earth. Construct an argument
from evidence supporting the idea that eukaryotes could not exist on the planet if not for
prokaryotes.

DF43248F3CB04B6AB99250FD168BA2BC.description:
Obtain information and construct an explanation to support or oppose an adaptive advantage of
social behaviors.

CE5DF6EE481740A8AAFF0A5E94615591.description:
Compare innate versus learned behavior. Construct an argument from evidence that shows the
value of both types of behavior and their importance to species survival.

82E4CDBDDFDB40EDA61B875D029E095D.description:
Plan and carry out an ethology investigation of a simple organism. Gather, analyze, and present
data in tabular and graphical formats. Draw conclusions based on data and communicate
findings.
